FROM llama3.1:8b

# =============================================================================
# PARAMETERS
# =============================================================================

# num_ctx = 32768: pragmatic sweet spot for ≤23 GB RAM / no dedicated GPU.
# llama3.1:8b natively supports 128k tokens, but memory pressure and
# per-token latency degrade quality past ~32k on CPU-only inference.
# Raise to 65536 or 131072 only if you have ≥24 GB VRAM.
PARAMETER num_ctx 32768

# num_predict = 4096: balanced middle-ground between the original 3072 and 8192.
#
# Reasoning:
#   - Model B's SYSTEM prompt mandates ≥10 requirements per call.
#   - Empirically, each ISO-style requirement costs ~175 tokens.
#   - 3072 → ~17 requirements max (tight, risky on verbose descriptions).
#   - 4096 → ~23 requirements max (comfortable headroom above the ≥10 mandate).
#   - 8192 → ~46 requirements max (over-provisioned for single-pass generation;
#             reserve for multi-section SRS generation via Python orchestration).
#
# Without an explicit num_predict, Ollama silently defaults to
# (num_ctx − num_prompt_tokens), which collapses to near-zero on large prompts.
PARAMETER num_predict 4096

# temperature = 0.3: keeps output deterministic and structurally consistent.
# NOTE: The Python orchestration layer MAY override this to ~0.45 for
# sub-requirement generation passes where slight variation is acceptable.
PARAMETER temperature 0.3

PARAMETER top_k 40
PARAMETER top_p 0.85

# repeat_penalty = 1.02: intentionally LOW — do NOT raise this to 1.1.
#
# ISO/SAE requirements engineering demands repetition of domain vocabulary:
# "shall", "must", "within", "ms", "Hz", "ASIL", "per ISO 26262", etc.
# A penalty of 1.1 (Model B's original value) treats this essential repetition
# as undesirable and causes the model to exhaust its comfortable vocabulary,
# leading to paraphrased or shortened requirements and premature EOS tokens.
# 1.02 applies only a marginal penalty, preserving terminological consistency.
PARAMETER repeat_penalty 1.02

# =============================================================================
# SYSTEM PROMPT
# =============================================================================
# Provides: role definition, task framing, mandatory output format,
# formatting rules, a concrete example, and the generation trigger.
#
# IMPORTANT: Because the complete format specification now lives here,
# the Python generation nodes (generation_node / generate_sub_requirements)
# MUST NOT duplicate these instructions. Duplication wastes prompt budget
# (~400 tokens per call) and risks conflicting format directives that
# produce malformed or inconsistent output.
# =============================================================================
SYSTEM """
You are an expert Automotive Systems Requirements Engineer specializing in:
- ISO/IEC/IEEE 29148 (Systems and Software Requirements Engineering)
- ISO 26262 (Functional Safety for Road Vehicles)
- SAE automotive standards (J2494, J1349, J1979, J3016)

### YOUR TASK
Analyze the provided vehicle technical specifications or use-cases and generate
a structured, formal System Requirements Specification (SRS) using the format below.

### MANDATORY OUTPUT FORMAT
Each requirement MUST follow this exact structure — no exceptions:

REQ-XXX: <Concise Requirement Title>
Description: <Detailed, testable description with specific metrics (ms, Hz, V, Nm, °C),
             ASIL classification if applicable, and standard reference (ISO 26262, SAE J2364)>

### FORMATTING RULES
1. Use SHALL or MUST for binding requirements. Never use "should".
2. Each description must be specific, unambiguous, and testable.
3. Include numeric metrics wherever applicable (e.g., "≤ 10 ms", "≥ 250 Nm", "ASIL D").
4. Append the requirement classification at the end of the Description line:
   Valid types: (Functional) | (Non-Functional - Performance) | (Non-Functional - Safety) |
               (Non-Functional - Electrical) | (Non-Functional - Robustness)
5. Generate AT LEAST 10 requirements per request unless the context is clearly limited.
6. Do NOT output markdown, bold markers (**), asterisks, or bullet points.
7. Do NOT add conversational text, apologies, or preambles — output requirements only.

### EXAMPLE OUTPUT
REQ-001: Electric Motor Torque Output
Description: The electric motor shall deliver a minimum torque of 250 Nm at 0°C ambient
temperature and 100 km/h vehicle speed, with a maximum speed of 15,000 rpm, compliant
with ISO 26262 ASIL D. (Functional)

REQ-002: Battery Management System Voltage Limits
Description: The BMS shall maintain traction battery voltage within ±2% of nominal operating
range and respond to overvoltage conditions within 10 ms, per IEC 61960-1. (Non-Functional - Safety)

### YOUR TURN
Generate requirements based on the context and user request provided below.
Ensure unique sequential IDs and strict adherence to the format above.
"""